[src:masonite-python/active-record-pattern] In software engineering, the **active record pattern** is an architectural pattern.
[src:masonite-python/active-record-pattern] It is found in software that stores in-memory object data in relational databases.
[src:masonite-python/active-record-pattern] It was named by Martin Fowler in his 2003 book *Patterns of Enterprise Application Architecture*.
[src:masonite-python/active-record-pattern] The interface of an object conforming to this pattern would include functions such as Insert, Update, and Delete, plus properties that correspond more or less directly to the columns in the underlying database table.
[src:masonite-python/active-record-pattern] The Active Record pattern is a Data Access Layer that performs bidirectional transfer of data between a persistent data store (often a relational database) and an in-memory data representation (the domain layer).
[src:masonite-python/active-record-pattern] A database table or view is wrapped into a class.
[src:masonite-python/active-record-pattern] Thus, an object instance is tied to a single row in the table.
[src:masonite-python/active-record-pattern] After creation of an object, a new row is added to the table upon save.
[src:masonite-python/active-record-pattern] Any object loaded gets its information from the database.
[src:masonite-python/active-record-pattern] When an object is updated, the corresponding row in the table is also updated.
[src:masonite-python/active-record-pattern] The wrapper class implements accessor methods or properties for each column in the table or view.
[src:masonite-python/active-record-pattern] This pattern is commonly used by object persistence tools and in object–relational mapping (ORM).
[src:masonite-python/active-record-pattern] Typically, foreign key relationships will be exposed as an object instance of the appropriate type via a property.
[src:masonite-python/active-record-pattern] Implementations of the concept can be found in various frameworks for many programming environments.
[src:masonite-python/active-record-pattern] This will find a new `Part` object based on the first matching row from the `parts` table whose `name` column has the value "gearbox".
[src:masonite-python/active-record-pattern] Various libraries implement an active record pattern framework, such as POCO C++ Libraries in library `Poco::ActiveRecord`.
[src:masonite-python/active-record-pattern] This is a simple example of an active record object `User`, in Java.
[src:masonite-python/active-record-pattern] Here the `User` class is both the model and data access object and provides `save()`, `find()`, and `delete()` methods.
[src:masonite-python/active-record-pattern] Another critique of the active record pattern is that, due to the strong coupling of database interaction and application logic, an active record object does not follow the single responsibility principle and separation of concerns.
[src:masonite-python/active-record-pattern] This is opposed to multitier architecture, which properly addresses these practices.
[src:masonite-python/active-record-pattern] Because of this, the active record pattern is best and most often employed in simple applications that are all forms-over-data with CRUD functionality, or only as one part of an architecture.
[src:masonite-python/active-record-pattern] Typically that part is data access and why several ORMs implement the active record pattern.
